2025 tennis event results

Carlos Alcaraz defeated defending champion Jannik Sinner[1] in the final, 6–2, 3–6, 6–1, 6–4 to win the men's singles tennis title at the 2025 US Open.[2][3] It was his second US Open title and sixth major title overall. By winning the title, Alcaraz regained the world No. 1 singles ranking from Sinner.[4] Alcaraz was the youngest man to win six major titles since Björn Borg, as well as the fourth (and youngest) man in history to win multiple major singles titles on all three surfaces (clay, grass and hardcourt), after Mats Wilander, Rafael Nadal and Novak Djokovic.[5] Sinner was the fourth (and youngest) man in the Open Era to reach all four major finals in a season (after Rod Laver, Roger Federer, and Djokovic), and the youngest in the Open Era to reach five consecutive major finals. Alcaraz and Sinner became the first pair of men's singles players in the Open Era to contest three major finals in the same year.[6]

Djokovic was attempting to win a record-extending 25th major title,[7] but lost to Alcaraz in the semifinals.[8] This marked only the third year since 2007 where Djokovic did not contest a major final (after 2009 and 2017), and the first year since 2002 that none of Big Three contested a major final.[9] With his third-round win, Djokovic recorded his 192nd career match win at hardcourt majors, surpassing Federer's record.[10] At 38 years, 103 days of age, Djokovic became the oldest man to reach the US Open semifinals since Jimmy Connors in 1991, the oldest man to reach any major semifinal since Federer at the 2020 Australian Open, and the oldest man in the Open Era to reach all four major semifinals in a season.[11]

This marked the first time since 2010 that Grigor Dimitrov did not participate at a major, ending his streak of 58 consecutive major appearances.[12]

Coleman Wong became the first man from Hong Kong to qualify for a major main draw in the Open Era,[13][14] and the first to win a match at a major singles main draw since Ip Koon Hung and Edwin Tsai at the 1954 Wimbledon Championships—when Hong Kong was a British colony.[15] Wong was also one of five qualifiers (alongside Leandro Riedi, Jan-Lennard Struff, Ugo Blanchet, and Jérôme Kym) to reach the third round,[16] tied for the highest number in a single edition at the US Open in men's singles in the Open Era with 1984 and 2021.[17]

Ranked No. 435 (and using a protected ranking to enter the qualifying draw), Riedi was the lowest-ranked player to reach the fourth round of a major since Richard Krajicek at the 2002 Wimbledon Championships, and the lowest-ranked player to do so at the US Open since Jay Berger in 1985.[18]
